  "prompt": "Why does my dog only lick me all over?",
  "response": "There could be several reasons why your dog licks you frequently:\n\n1. Affection and bonding\n- Licking is a way dogs show love and strengthen their connection with you\n- It's a natural behavior learned from mother dogs grooming their puppies\n\n2. Taste\n- Dogs may enjoy the salt in human sweat\n- They might like the taste of skin products or food residue\n\n3. Submission and respect\n- Licking can be a sign of submission in dog social hierarchies\n- Your dog may see you as the pack leader\n\n4. Seeking attention\n- Dogs learn that licking often gets a reaction from their owners\n- It can be a way to get your attention or interaction\n\n5. Comfort and stress relief\n- Licking can be self-soothing for dogs\n- It releases endorphins that help them feel calm\n\n6. Communication\n- Dogs use licking to communicate various emotions or needs\n- It can signal anxiety, excitement, or a desire for something\n\n7. Instinctive behavior\n- In the wild, dogs lick to clean wounds or show care for pack members\n- This instinct can transfer to their relationship with humans\n\nIf the licking seems excessive, consult a veterinarian to rule out any underlying medical or behavioral issues.",
